dslRuleAfterChange:
A hypothetical rule might look like:
`return getPosAfterToken($pos, org.eclipse.jdt.internal.compiler.codegen.TerminalTokens.TokenNameLBRACE);
=> try {
    return getPosAfterToken($pos, org.eclipse.jdt.internal.compiler.codegen.TerminalTokens.TokenNameLBRACE);
} catch (java.lang.IllegalArgumentException $e) {
    return $pos;
}`
This is beyond the current DSL capabilities for multi-statement replacements with control flow.

dslRule:
new org.eclipse.jdt.core.dom.PackageBinding($packageBinding, this)
=> $packageBinding instanceof org.eclipse.jdt.internal.compiler.lookup.ProblemPackageBinding ? new org.eclipse.jdt.core.dom.RecoveredPackageBinding($packageBinding, this) : new org.eclipse.jdt.core.dom.PackageBinding($packageBinding, this)
;;

@id: jdt.internal.astmatcher.match-usesdirective-typefix
@severity: error
!(other instanceof org.eclipse.jdt.core.dom.UnionType) :: sourceVersionGE(9)
=> !(other instanceof org.eclipse.jdt.core.dom.UsesDirective)
;;

@id: jdt.internal.requiresdirective.modulemodifier-cast-fix
@severity: error
((org.eclipse.jdt.core.dom.Modifier) $x).getKeyword().toFlagValue() :: sourceVersionGE(9)
=> ((org.eclipse.jdt.core.dom.ModuleModifier) $x).getKeyword().toFlagValue()
;;
